About
Through commemoration, exhibitions and educational programs, The National September 11 Memorial & Museum, a nonprofit in New York City, remembers and honors the 2,983 people killed in the horrific attacks of September 11, 2001, and February 26, 1993, as well as those who risked their lives to save others and all who demonstrated extraordinary compassion in the aftermath of the attacks. 9/11 Memorial, Open Daily, 7-days, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. 9/11 Memorial Museum, Open Thursdayâ€“Monday, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Thanksgiving and Christmas: Memorial Only, 10 a.m. to 4 p.m.; Museum Closed
Duration: 2-3 hours

karlee f

Not what I expected, but glad I went once.
Nov 2024 â€¢ Couples
It's hard to write this review knowing what the Museum stands for.
First, the pools are beautiful and it is truly a space of respect in the city.
However, I can only give the museum a 3 star review.
It's practically an art museum, highlighting pieces that artists have created in remembrance of the situation.
Besides that,
one room in particular has the faces/portraits hanging up of all the people that were killed during the attack. It puts the event into a whole new meaning when you see that.
There's another "history" exhibit that has more of what I expected in it. Voices of family members who lost loved ones, personal memorabilia, fire trucks and police cars damaged when the tower fell, news broadcasts and images from the day of the attack.
I'm glad I came and paid my respects, but I expected something more interactive like at the Holocaust museum in Washington, DC.
